# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: api-gateway-patterns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] A server that acts as an API front-end receives API requests, enforces throttling and security policies, passes requests to the back-end service and then passes the response back to the requester.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] A gateway often includes a transformation engine to orchestrate and modify the requests and responses on the fly.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] A gateway can also provide functions such as collecting analytics data and providing caching.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] The gateway can provide the functionality to support authentication, authorization, security, audit and regulatory compliance.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] Functionality to monitor API usage and load (overall hits, completed transactions, number of data objects returned, amount of compute time and other internal resources consumed, the volume of data transferred).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] This can include real-time API monitoring with alerts being raised directly or via a higher-level network management system, for instance, if the load on an API has become too great, as well as functionality to analyze historical data, such as transaction logs, to detect usage trends.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] Functionality can also be provided to create synthetic transactions that can be used to test the performance and behavior of API endpoints.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] The API provider can use the information gathered by the reporting and analytics functionality to optimize the API offering within an organization's overall continuous improvement process and define software Service-Level Agreements for APIs.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] Functionality to support charging for access to commercial APIs.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] This functionality can include support for setting up pricing rules based on usage, load and functionality, issuing invoices, and collecting payments, including multiple types of credit card payments.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] Several industry analysts have observed that the market size for API management solutions has been growing rapidly since the early 2010s.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] Gartner estimated the market size for API management to be $70 million in 2013, growing at 40% a year.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/api-management] According to Forrester Research, in the US alone, annual spend on API management was $140 million in 2014, expected to grow to $660 million by 2020, with total global sales predicted to exceed a billion dollars by that year.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
