[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] documents within a given set of services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The relationship between services is minimized to the level that they are only aware of their existence.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be called from anywhere within the network that it is located no matter where it is present.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services should be designed to be long lived.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Where possible, services should avoid forcing consumers to change if they do not require new features; if you call a service today, you should be able to call the same service tomorrow.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The services act as black boxes, that is their inner logic is hidden from the consumers.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are independent and control the functionality they encapsulate, from a Design-time and a run-time perspective.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are stateless, that is either return the requested value or give an exception hence minimizing resource use.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A principle to ensure services have an adequate size and scope.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The functionality provided by the service to the user must be relevant.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are decomposed or consolidated (normalized) to minimize redundancy.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] These are the cases where performance optimization, access, and aggregation are required.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be used to compose other services.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are supplemented with communicative meta data by which they can be effectively discovered and interpreted.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Logic is divided into various services, to promote reuse of code.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Many services which were not initially planned under SOA, may get encapsulated or become a part of SOA.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] It creates a web service and provides its information to the service registry.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] and what sort of trading partner agreements are required to use the service.
