[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Application programming interfaces (APIs) are the frameworks through which developers can interact with a web application.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Tim O'Reilly coined the term "Web 2.0" to describe a perceived, quickly growing set of web-based applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A topic that has experienced extensive coverage involves the relationship between Web 2.0 and service-oriented architectures.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is the philosophy of encapsulating application logic in services with a uniformly defined interface and making these publicly available via discovery mechanisms.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The notion of complexity-hiding and reuse, but also the concept of loosely coupling services has inspired researchers to elaborate on similarities between the two philosophies, SOA and Web 2.0, and their respective applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Some argue Web 2.0 and SOA have significantly different elements and thus can not be regarded "parallel philosophies", whereas others consider the two concepts as complementary and regard Web 2.0 as the global SOA.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The philosophies of Web 2.0 and SOA serve different user needs and thus expose differences with respect to the design and also the technologies used in real-world applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] However, as of 2008, use-cases demonstrated the potential of combining technologies and principles of both Web 2.0 and SOA.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Microservices are a modern interpretation of service-oriented architectures used to build distributed software systems.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services in a microservice architecture are processes that communicate with each other over the network in order to fulfill a goal.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] These services use technology agnostic protocols, which aid in encapsulating choice of language and frameworks, making their choice a concern internal to the service.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Microservices are a new realisation and implementation approach to SOA, which have become popular since 2014 (and after the introduction of DevOps), and which also emphasize continuous deployment and other agile practices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] There is no single commonly agreed definition of microservices.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Interactive applications requiring real-time response times, for example low-latency interactive 3d applications, are using specific service oriented architectures addressing the specific needs of such kind of applications.
[src:api-gateway-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] These include for example low-latency optimized distributed computation and communication as well as resource and instance management.
